Read more at the link in bio.

Incandescent lava coursed from a ridge on the island of La Palma last year. Homes, shops, churches, cropland, and schools once sat in the 3.5 miles between the new volcano and the sea. Now they’re all entombed in stone, and the community is facing a landscape that's forever changed.

Photo and video by Carsten Peter

node.text: Video by @joelsartore | This adorable female desert hedgehog can be found throughout much of northern Africa and the Arabian Peninsula. To avoid the desert heat, these critters will spend most of the day sleeping, often near rocks and cliffs that help conceal them from birds of prey. Once the sun goes down, the hedgehogs will prowl for insects and other prey species. Video taken @epaa_shj. node.text: Video by Pete McBride @pedromcbride | The brevity of time and life quickly becomes evident when filming the funeral pyres on the banks of India's Ganges River in Varanasi, a pilgrimage center for Hindus. From our documentary film "Holy (un)Holy River," which focused on the contamination of this river. node.text: Video by @joelsartore | Raccoons, like this crab-eating raccoon at @elparquedelasleyendas in Lima, Peru, have some of the most nimble hands seen in nature. In fact, this species was actually named for its skillful paws, with “raccoon” coming from the Powhatan word “aroughcun” (when translated, this means “animal that scratches with its hands”). While most animals rely on sight, scent, or sound to hunt, these mammals depend on their sense of touch to locate food. To heighten this sense, raccoons will do something called dousing, in which they wet their paws to stimulate nerve endings. To see more species featured in the Photo Ark, follow @joelsartore. #raccoon #crabeating #mammal #animal #wildlife #video #footage #dousing #hands #paws #washing #PhotoArk

node.text: Video by @bertiegregory | Lion cubs play in Zambia’s South Luangwa National Park. These cubs belong to a pride that specializes in hunting buffalo. So while this cub play might look like fun, it’s critical training for adult life when they’ll be helping the pride bring down lunch. Filmed for my new show coming later this year to @disneyplus. #EpicAdventuresWithBertieGregory

node.text: Video by @joelsartore | Helmeted hornbills are glorious birds—and coveted in the illegal wildlife trade for their solid casques, or helmets. Softer than ivory, they can be carved into beads and statuary. As if sensing the threat, these birds fiercely protect their young: The male helps seal the female inside the cavity of a tree for months, bringing food to her and the chick through a tiny slit. When it’s time for the young to fledge, the hornbills chisel away the seal. A logger who’d heard the birds squawking inside a tree that was cut down brought them to Malaysia’s @penangbirdpark. These hornbills were lucky. Deforestation is a major threat to this species’ survival, and in most cases, birds still sealed inside a tree would die. But this man knew how rare they were and brought them to the bird park. It’s not easy to keep these birds alive when their habitat has disappeared. To see more species featured in the Photo Ark follow me, @joelsartore. #bird #hornbill #helmeted #casque #animal #wildlife #saveourwildlife #video #PhotoArk

node.text: Video by @joelsartore | A giant desert centipede scurries across the frame during a Photo Ark shoot @melbournemuseum in Australia. This species can be found in both dry and moist habitats, usually in sheltered places such as under logs or rocks or in leaf litter. A solitary predator, the giant centipede may bite if disturbed or handled—while painful, the bite from this species is not fatal. To see more species featured in the Photo Ark follow me @joelsartore. #centipede #giant #wildlife #animal #video #australia #PhotoArk

Video by Muhammed Muheisen @mmuheisen | I believe that children are the real victims of conflict. They do not get to choose where they are born or their circumstances. Children from all over the world share the same things in common: They all seek fun, joy, and happiness. In this video, a group of Afghan refugees plays on the outskirts of Islamabad, Pakistan. 

Today is World Refugee Day, observed on June 20 each year and dedicated to raising awareness of the plight of those throughout the world who have been forced to flee their homes. For more photos and videos of the refugee crisis, follow me @mmuheisen and @mmuheisenpublic. For more on how to get involved, follow @everydayrefugees. #MuhammedMuheisen #EverydayRefugees #WorldRefugeeDay #MakingaDifference

The toughest place on Earth to be an elephant may be the Namib Desert in southern Africa. With temperatures that can surpass 120 degrees Fahrenheit and less than three inches of rainfall a year, the desert is a land of extremes. Nonetheless, a group of 150 elephants is managing to survive. 

Watch #SecretsOfTheElephants, now streaming on @disneyplus and @hulu.

node.text: Photo by David Guttenfelder @dguttenfelder | The sun sets over Lake Superior’s York Island, one of the 21 islands that make up the Apostle Islands National Lakeshore, seen from the grounds of Raspberry Island lighthouse. The archipelago, which is Ojibwe Native land and the heart of the Anishinaabe story of creation, has been a protected national lakeshore since 1970. The name for the Apostle Islands in Ojibwe is Wenabozho Ominisan. According to the National Park Service, this translates to a possessive relationship between the cultural hero Wenabozho and his ownership of the islands, since he is the one who made them. Read the full story on the Apostle Islands at the link in bio.

Video and art by National Geographic Explorer Tara Keir @tarankeir | As a creative storyteller, I believe art holds such power as a storytelling medium. When paired with thought-provoking words and hard-hitting facts, we can creatively connect people with conservation stories in ways that deeply resonate, particularly when it comes to exploring how humans and wildlife intersect.

To be in the presence of elephants is to feel deeply connected. These quirky, charming, complex beings embody a magic that beautifully blurs the separation we’ve constructed between humans and wildlife. Emotions that were once thought to exclusively define the human experience–love, grief, empathy, and joy–are ones that we undeniably share with elephants. Given the profound similarities connecting us, it is difficult to swallow the truth that humans are currently the greatest threat to wild elephants’ survival. Because of poaching for their ivory tusks, habitat destruction, and human encroachment, African elephant populations continue to decrease dramatically. To ensure a future with living, thriving elephants, perhaps there are lessons in coexistence to be found within these deep human-wildlife connections.

Photo by Daniella Zalcman @dzalcman | This is Francis “Frannie” White, a member of the Coeur d’Alene tribe in Idaho. She attended the Mary Immaculate School at the Mission of the Sacred Heart in DeSmet. “One of the first things my grandmother told me when I was getting ready to go to boarding school was, ‘When the nuns beat on you, don’t give them the pleasure of seeing you cry.’ I asked, ‘So what do I do?’ She said, ‘Laugh.’”

Frannie had a horrific experience at boarding school and, at one point in the 1980s as an adult, went to the site of the old school with matches and gasoline, intent on burning down the building. She didn’t go through with it, but in 2011, when the school was destroyed in a fire, she said she celebrated. Frannie is now an active elder in her community, attending Coeur d’Alene language classes multiple times a week and taking long walks around nearby lakes. “I’ve been learning who I am and how to be comfortable with who I am and to take pride in who I am. I’m still going through that process. But we have to learn about what has been stolen from us. Was it stolen, or is it just sleeping?”

Read about the history of Indian boarding school systems at the link in bio, or pick up the May issue of National Geographic. This artwork was supported by @insidenatgeo.

node.text: Video by @carltonward | During the making of the new film “Path of the Panther,” directed by @bendicci, we relied heavily on custom-made camera traps to capture images of the elusive Florida panther, the only puma in the eastern United States. The species has recovered from fewer than 20 individuals in the 1970s to nearly 200 today and is mainly isolated to the southern tip of Florida. To ever recover from their current endangered status, panthers need to grow in number and reclaim more of their historic territory further north in the state. That makes protecting the Florida Wildlife Corridor essential for the revival of the species, which is among the most difficult to see and film in the wild. In a lifetime of exploring Florida, I have only seen two panthers in the wild with my own eyes. Fortunately, the camera traps allowed the panthers to take their own pictures—or, in this case, ultra-high-definition video. This video was captured in 4K resolution by a camera trap that the @pathofthepanther team and I had focused on this Everglades trail for more than two years. We’re excited to share more rare footage of these animals in the debut of “Path of the Panther,” coming to National Geographic TV on April 22, Hulu on April 23, and Disney+ on April 28! #pathofthepanther

Video by @danwintersphoto | After a Monday, April 17, scrub, SpaceX launched its Starship rocket today at 8:33 a.m. CT in South Texas. The tallest and most powerful rocket ever launched cleared the pad, roared into the sky, and successfully passed through a key moment of heavy aerodynamic stress. The plan was for the Super Heavy booster to separate from the spacecraft. Instead, it began flipping and broke apart midflight.

The rocket possesses about twice the thrust of the Apollo Saturn V, which launched astronauts to the moon in the 1960s and ’70s. Starship, which is considered pivotal to the future of SpaceX, is also crucial for future human space exploration: It’s part of NASA’s Artemis program to land on the moon. Read the full story at the link in bio and follow me, @danwintersphoto, for continuing coverage of the NASA Artemis program.

node.text: Photo by Robbie Shone @shonephoto | Slovenia's Zelske cave lies at the base of several natural rock bridges. In the background, two explorers walk under one of the "skylights" where, long ago, the cave's roof collapsed. This beautiful arched portal was shaped over hundreds of thousands of years by constant erosion from the River Rak.
